{{refimprove|date=February 2017}} [[File:Byblos Castle 2009.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Byblos Castle]] [[Image:ByblosCrusaderCastle1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Byblos Castle]] '''Byblos Castle''' is a [[Crusader castle]] in [[Byblos]], [[Lebanon]]. In Crusader times it was known as the '''castle of Gibelet''' or '''Giblet'''.<ref name="Notre Dame">{{cite web |title= Crusader Castle, Byblos: Overall view, castle and surrounding groves |author=G. Massiot & cie |work= Architectural Lantern Slides of Lebanon |publisher= Hesburgh Libraries, University of Notre Dame, Indiana |date= |url= https://curate.nd.edu/show/pn89d507r18 | quote= Byblos... Under the name of Gibelet or Giblet... |accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>
==History== The castle was built by the [[Crusaders]] in the 12th century from indigenous limestone and the remains of Roman structures. The finished structure was surrounded by a moat. It belonged to the [[Genoa|Genoese]] [[Embriaco family]], whose members were the Lords of Gibelet. [[Saladin]] captured the town and castle in 1188 and partially dismantled the walls in 1190. Later, the Crusaders recaptured Byblos and rebuilt the fortifications of the castle in 1197. In 1369, the castle had to fend off an attack from [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] vessels from [[Famagusta]].<ref name="Byblos Castle">{{cite web |title=Byblos Castle |url= http://travelinos.com/castles/n22-18625-Byblos_Castle |accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref>
The Byblos Castle has distinguished historical buildings for neighbors. Nearby stand a few Egyptian temples, the [[Phoenicia]]n royal [[necropolis]] and the [[Roman amphitheatre]].<ref name="Byblos Castle"/>
==Description== The Crusader castle of Gibelet is "the finest example" (Boas) of a new 12th-century type, which mixes the ''[[castrum]]''-type with the ''[[donjon|turris]]''-type castle:<ref>{{cite book |title= Archaeology of the Military Orders: A Survey of the Urban Centres, Rural Settlements and Castles of the Military Orders in the Latin East (c.1120-1291) |author=Adrian Boas |year=2006 |publisher= Routledge |url={{Google books |id=e-2BAgAAQBAJ |page=57 |plainurl=yes}} |isbn=9781134422838 |accessdate=15 December 2017 }}</ref> a roughly square set of walls strengthened by corner towers, built around a central [[donjon]],<ref>David Nicolle, ''Crusader Castles in the Holy Land 1097-1192'', Osprey, 2004, [http://faravashi.ir/download/2004-28579.pdf pp. 11-12]</ref> thus forming two layers of defense.
==Byblos Site Museum== [[File:ByblosSiteMuseum1.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Limestone anchor (1800 BCE)]] [[File:Byblos Crusader Castle Museum.jpg|thumb|Exhibits at the museum inside the Byblos Castle]] The castle houses the Byblos site museum. It displays remains of the excavations undertaken on the site of the archeological preserve of Byblos, although the most important finds are displayed in the [[National Museum of Beirut]]. Moreover, the history of Byblos from prehistory to the medieval periods, is illustrated with thematic panels.<ref>[http://livelovelebanon.com/en/byblos-site-museum The Byblos Site Museum]</ref>
==Bibliography== * ''Je m'appelle Byblos'', [[Jean-Pierre Thiollet]], H & D, 2005. {{ISBN|2 914 266 04 9}}
