{{dynamic list|date=April 2017}} This is a '''list of people declared ''persona non grata'''''. ''[[Persona non grata]]'' ([[Latin]], [[plural]]: ''personae non gratae''), literally meaning "an unwelcome person", is a legal term used in [[diplomacy]] that indicates a proscription against a foreign person entering or remaining in the country. It is the most serious form of censure that one country can apply to foreign diplomats, who are otherwise protected by [[diplomatic immunity]] from [[arrest]] and other normal kinds of prosecution.
{{multiple image | direction = vertical | width = 130 | footer = | image1 = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-M0921-014, Beglaubigungsschreiben DDR-Vertreter in UNO new.png | alt1 = Kurt Waldheim | caption1 = [[Kurt Waldheim]] | image2 = Kennan.jpeg | alt2 = George F. Kennan | caption2 = [[George F. Kennan]] | image3 = Vargas Losa Göteborg Book Fair 2011b.jpg | alt3 = Mario Vargas Llosa | caption3 = [[Mario Vargas Llosa]] | image4 = Carl Bildt under nationaldagsfirande vid Skansen 2009.jpg | alt4 = Carl Bildt | caption4 = [[Carl Bildt]] | image5 = Jörg Haider 04-09-2008.jpg | alt5 = Jörg Haider | caption5 = [[Jörg Haider]] | image6 = Philipgoldberg.jpg | alt6 = Philip Goldberg | caption6 = [[Philip Goldberg]] | image7 = George Galloway 2007-02-24.jpg | alt7 = George Galloway | caption7 = [[George Galloway]] | image8 = László Sólyom.jpg | alt8 = László Sólyom | caption8 = [[László Sólyom]] | image9 = Günter Grass, 2004.jpg | alt9 = Günter Grass | caption9 = [[Günter Grass]] | image10 = Montserrat Caballé.jpg | alt10 = Montserrat Caballé | caption10 = [[Montserrat Caballé]] | image11 = | alt11 = | caption11 = | caption12 = [[Brad Pitt]] | image12 = Brad Pitt June 2014 (cropped).jpg | alt12 = Brad Pitt | caption13 = [[Claire Danes]] | image13 = Claire Danes.jpg | alt13 = Claire Danes }}
* The [[Treaty of Lausanne]] in 1923 included the list of [[150 personae non gratae of Turkey|150 ''personae non gratae'' of Turkey]], which forbade the entry of mainly a group of former [[Ottoman Empire]] officials and about 100 other persons to [[Turkey]], until the lifting of this status in 1938.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} * [[Chiune Sugihara]], who helped several thousand Jews in Lithuania in the 1940s, was declared ''persona non grata'' by the Soviet Union in 1947.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} * [[Queen Victoria Eugenie of Spain]] was obliged to leave Italy in 1942 having become ''persona non grata'' to the Italian government. According to [[Harold Tittmann]], a United States representative at the Vatican at the time, this was due to her "ill-disguised leanings to the Allied cause."<ref>Harold Tittmann, ''Inside the Vatican of Pius XI'', p. 32, Image book, Doubleday, 2004.</ref> * [[Harald Edelstam]], Swedish ambassador to Chile, was declared ''persona non grata'' for his efforts to hide and assist members of the opposition facing persecution by the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973–1990)|Chilean junta]] of 1973–1990, including occupying the Embassy of [[Cuba]] in [[Santiago]], containing hundreds of refugees, and declaring it Swedish soil. * [[Kurt Waldheim]], former [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] and [[President of Austria]], and his wife were given ''persona non grata'' status in the United States and other countries when he was accused of having known about [[Nazi war crime]]s and not having done anything about them.<ref name="waldheim1">{{cite news |url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/w/kurt_waldheim/index.html |title=Kurt Waldheim |access-date=January 1, 2009 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Serge|last=Schmemann}}</ref> * In September 1952, the American Ambassador to the Soviet Union, [[George F. Kennan]], was declared ''persona non grata'' after making a statement which the Soviets believed linked them to Nazi Germany. The Soviets refused to allow Kennan to reenter the Soviet Union.<ref>Kennan, George F. (1967), ''Memoirs: 1925–1950'', Boston: Little, Brown and Company, OCLC 484922. 152</ref> * In March 1976, [[Herbert Spiro]], the [[United States Ambassador to Cameroon]], also [[United States Ambassador to Equatorial Guinea|accredited to Equatorial Guinea]], was declared ''persona non grata'' by Equatorial Guinea. At the end of a visit to the country which he described as pleasant and uneventful up to that point, Equatoguinean Deputy Protocol Director [[Santiago Nchama]] handed him a letter accusing the United States government of engaging in subversive activities there, and days later, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation (Equatorial Guinea)|Equatorial Guinea's foreign ministry]] sent a telegram to the State Department announcing that Spiro and Consul William C. Mithoefer Jr, who had accompanied him on his visit, were both barred from the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19760315&id=sP0xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YuUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6878,2150846|title=Snub snaps U.S. ties with Equatorial Guinea|work=Lawrence Journal-World|date=March 15, 1976|access-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref> * In April 1979, the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s expert on [[Iran]], [[George Cave (CIA agent)|George W. Cave]], was declared ''persona non grata'' by the [[Iranian government]].<ref name="Participant Biographies">{{cite web |url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Iran%20conference%20bios.pdf |title=The Cold War International History Project / The National Security Archive / The Middle East Program&nbsp;— Participant Biographies |author=<!-- Staff writer(s); no by-line. --> |date= |website=www.wilsoncenter.org |publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars |access-date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> * In the 1990s, [[Mario Vargas Llosa]], who would later receive the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], was "''persona non grata'' in [[Peru]], discredited and insulted in the official press" of [[Alberto Fujimori]]'s regime. According to [[Ilan Stavans]], "Peruvians have made it a sport to hate Vargas Llosa."<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Maya Jaggi|first=Maya|last=Jaggi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/mar/16/fiction.books?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Fiction and hyper-reality|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 16, 2002|quote="During Fujimori's first two years I was very discreet," he says. "But I've been against dictatorships all my life. My situation became very difficult: I was persona non grata in Peru, discredited and insulted in the official press&nbsp;— Fujimori controlled everything. It was difficult because I couldn't respond."}}</ref> * In 1995, [[Croatia]] declared [[Carl Bildt]] ''persona non grata'' announcing that he had "lost the credibility necessary for the role of a peace mediator". Bildt had suggested that the President of Croatia, [[Franjo Tuđman]] was as guilty of war crimes as the Krajina Serb leader, [[Milan Martić]].<ref name="bnetcroatia">{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_/ai_n13999209 |title=Flight from Croatia: Refugee column hit from the air |access-date=January 1, 2009 |author=Emma Daly |date=August 8, 1995 |publisher=BNET |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814170424/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_/ai_n13999209 |archivedate=August 14, 2013 |df=}} </ref> * [[Brad Pitt]] became ''persona non grata'' in the [[People's Republic of China]] after he appeared in the 1997 film ''[[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]]''. The ban was lifted in 2014 when he accompanied his wife [[Angelina Jolie]] on a film promotion tour.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Chinafilminsider.com|date=October 27, 2016|access-date=July 19, 2018|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/brad-pitt-set-promote-allied-china-ending-two-decade-ban/|title=Brad Pitt Set To Promote ‘Allied’ In China, Ending Two-Decade ‘Ban’}}</ref> * In 1998, actress [[Claire Danes]], after the shooting for the film ''[[Brokedown Palace]]'' was completed, was labeled ''persona non grata'' by the [[Philippines|Philippine government]] after she commented in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' that [[Manila]] was a "ghastly and weird city".<ref>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|date=September 9, 1998|access-date=July 28, 2007|url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/News/9809/23/showbuzz/|title=Claire Danes no thrilla for Manila}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=October 10, 1998|access-date=July 28, 2007|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/1998/10/01/entertainment/main18857.shtml|title=Manila Is Mad At Claire Danes}}</ref> * In 2000, [[Israel]] declared [[Austrians|Austrian]] politician [[Jörg Haider]] ''persona non grata'' following the [[Austrian legislative election, 1999|Austrian legislative election of 1999]], since his right-wing populist [[Freedom Party of Austria]] ({{lang-de|Freiheitliche Partei Österreichs}}, FPÖ) was a member of the Austrian coalition government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/opinion/let-s-hear-it-for-the-haiders-1.203725 |title=Let's hear it for the Haiders |access-date=April 9, 2012|author=Akiva Eldar |date=October 30, 2006 |work=Haaretz}}</ref> * On February 19, 2000, the United States declared Jose Imperatori—a vice consul assigned to the [[Cuban Interests Section|Cuban interests section]] of the [[Embassy of Switzerland in Washington, D.C.|Swiss embassy]]—''persona non grata''. Imperatori was accused of acting as an intermediary to assist Mariano Faget in his alleged spying activities. Imperatori refused to leave and was eventually physically expelled on February 26, 2000.<ref>{{cite book |last=Murphy |first=Sean |date=2011 |title=United States Practice in International Law: Volume 1, 1999-2001 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=26–27 |isbn=0521299608}}</ref> * In 2007, the [[Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands]] (CNMI) House of Representatives voted [[Saipan]] resident and United States citizen Ron Hodges ''persona non grata'' by [[Resolution (law)|resolution]].<ref>[http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=15&newsID=74684 Saipantribune.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405193415/http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?cat=15&newsID=74684 |date=2012-04-05}}</ref> Hodges was castigated for his letter writing campaign critical of CNMI governance and abuses against alien workers, entitled [[Chamberonomics]].<ref>[http://unheardnomore.blogspot.com/2008/01/chamberonomics-series-1-29-highlights.html Blogspot.com]</ref> His letters supported a United States takeover of CNMI labor and immigration. Labor and human abuses in the CNMI garment industry had long been the subject of international criticism. The resolution's validity hinged on the question of CNMI sovereignty, but was never enforced and became moot after President Bush signed the [[Consolidated Natural Resources Act of 2008]]<ref>Consolidated Natural Resources Act of 2008, ({{USStatute|110|229|122|754|2008|05|09}})</ref> into law,<ref>[http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=79507&cat=1 Saipantribune.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405193426/http://www.saipantribune.com/newsstory.aspx?newsID=79507&cat=1 |date=2012-04-05}}</ref> thus federalizing CNMI labor and immigration.<ref name="cnmi2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonwatch.com/bills/show/110_HR_3079.html |title=Chamberonomics "spit in the soup" |access-date=December 6, 2007 |author=Ron Hodges |date=December 6, 2007 |publisher=Marianas Variety News}}</ref> * In 2008, [[President of Bolivia]] [[Evo Morales]] declared United States Ambassador [[Philip Goldberg]] ''persona non grata'', claiming that the United States government conspired against him and supported his opponents.<ref name="usbolivia2008">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/73005.htm |title=Biography of Philip S. Goldberg |access-date=January 9, 2009 |publisher=United States Department of State |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915083851/http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/73005.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2008}}</ref> * Soon after Bolivia's expulsion of Goldberg, [[President of Venezuela]] [[Hugo Chavez]] declared United States Ambassador [[Patrick Duddy]] ''persona non grata'' in solidarity with Morales' action. Chavez did not cite any specific alleged infractions by Duddy. * In October 2008 [[Serbia]] expelled ambassadors of [[Montenegro]] and the [[Republic of Macedonia]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,3704625,00.html |title=Serbia Expels Macedonian, Montenegrin Envoys Over Kosovo |date=October 10, 2008|access-date=April 9, 2009 |work=Deutsche Welle Online}}</ref> after these countries recognized the independence of [[Kosovo]]. In November 2008 [[Serbia]] also expelled the ambassador from [[Malaysia]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/worldlatest/story/0,,-7969763,00.html |title=Serbia expels Malaysia's ambassador, EU |date=November 1, 2008 |access-date=April 9, 2009 |work=The Guardian |location=London |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517071759/http://www.guardian.co.uk/worldlatest/story/0%2C%2C-7969763%2C00.html |archivedate=May 17, 2009 |df=}}</ref> after Malaysia recognized Kosovo's independence. * In 2008 the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Israel)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] of [[Israel]] declared [[United States|American]] [[Richard A. Falk]], [[Princeton University]] [[professor emeritus]] of [[international law]], ''persona non grata''<ref>[http://en.trend.az/regions/met/israel/1371879.html "Foreign Ministry of Israel declares UN expert ''persona non grata''"], [[Trend News Agency]], December 15, 2008. * Mel Frykberg, [http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=43056 "When You Shoot the Messenger"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111080610/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=43056 |date=2012-01-11}}, [[Inter Press Service]], July 3, 2008. * David Cronin, [http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=45509 "Cornering of Civilians Unprecedented, Says UN Official"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111080919/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=45509 |date=2012-01-11}}, Inter Press Service, January 22, 2009.</ref> when he was the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s [[United Nations Special Rapporteur]] on "the situation of human rights in the [[Palestinian Territories|Palestinian territories]] occupied since 1967."<ref>{{cite web|title=Human Rights Council elects Advisory Committee Members and approves a number of Special Procedures mandate holders|publisher=[[United Nations]]|date=March 26, 2008|url=http://domino.un.org/UNISPAL.nsf/2ee9468747556b2d85256cf60060d2a6/0da4ba56ade85249852574190058d462!OpenDocument|access-date=January 1, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5dViuhEdA?url=http://domino.un.org/UNISPAL.nsf/2ee9468747556b2d85256cf60060d2a6/0da4ba56ade85249852574190058d462!OpenDocument|archivedate=January 1, 2009|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> Stating this was because Falk previously had compared Israel's treatment of Palestinians to [[Nazism|Nazi]] treatment of Jews,<ref>[http://www.forward.com/articles/13037 "U.N. Taps American Jewish Critic of Israel as Rights Expert"], ''[[The Forward]]'', April 4, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1206446111162&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull "UNHRC appointment infuriates Israel"]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', March 26, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/972974.html "Israel to bar UN official for comparing Israelis to Nazis"], ''Haaretz'', April 8, 2008.</ref> Israel barred him in May 2008<ref>[http://www.commondreams.org/news2008/0423-05.htm Press Release: National Lawyers Guild Urges Israel to Permit Richard Falk to Enter Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories], [[Common Dreams]], April 23, 2008.</ref><ref>Linda Mamoun, [http://www.alternet.org/module/printversion/91225 "Israel Bars UN Human Rights Watchdog From Occupied Territories"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406100847/http://www.alternet.org/module/printversion/91225 |date=2012-04-06}}, [[Alternet]] reprint of ''[[The Nation]]'' article, posted on July 11, 2008.</ref> and December 2008.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3638881,00.html "Israel denies entry to UN rights investigator"], [[Reuters]], reproduced at [[YNET]], December 15, 2008.</ref><ref>Richard A. Falk, [http://www.palestine-pmc.com/details.asp?cat=4&id=3930 "My Expulsion from Israel"], December 22, 2008.</ref> As of March 2011, Falk was still banned from Israel.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4045623,00.html UN official: Israel engaging in ethnic cleansing], Reuters, March 21, 2011.</ref> * On December 23, 2008, [[Fiji]] followed through on a threat to expel [[New Zealand]]'s high commissioner to the island nation. The expulsion came a day after the interim [[Prime Minister of Fiji]] announced he would not expel New Zealand's top diplomat because he wanted to improve his relationship with New Zealand. In retaliation to the expulsion, New Zealand declared Fiji's High Commissioner in Wellington ''persona non grata'' as [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] [[John Key]] had stated the day before that there would be retaliatory action if its commissioner was expelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10549546&ref=rss |title=NZ and Fiji expel high commissioners |date=December 23, 2008 |access-date=July 28, 2009 |work=New Zealand Herald}}</ref> * In January 2009, following [[Venezuela]] expelling Israeli diplomats due to Israel's offensive in the [[Gaza Strip]], [[Israel]] ordered Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country, declaring them ''personae non gratae'' in Israel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/7856612.stm |title=Israel expels Venezuela envoy |date=January 28, 2009|access-date=February 1, 2009 |publisher=BBC News Online}}</ref> * In March 2009, President Evo Morales of Bolivia declared a member of the United States embassy (political division) ''persona non grata''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsvote.bbc.co.uk/mpapps/pagetools/print/news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7933846.stm?ad=1 |title=Bolivia orders US diplomat to go |date=March 9, 2009 |access-date=February 1, 2009 |publisher=BBC News Online}}</ref> * On April 8, 2009, [[President of Moldova]] [[Vladimir Voronin]] declared [[Romania]]n Ambassador Filip Teodorescu and Councilor-Minister Ioan Gaborean ''personae non gratae'', claiming that "their activity was inconsistent with their diplomatic status"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,4162384,00.html |title=Moldovan president accuses Romania of being behind protests|date=April 8, 2009 |access-date=April 9, 2009 |work=Deutsche Welle Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=13774498&PageNum=0 |title=Moldova declares 2 Romanian diplomats ''persona non grata'' |date=April 8, 2009 |access-date=April 9, 2009 |publisher=ITAR-TASS News Agency}}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> after the Moldovan flag on the Parliament building was torn down and replaced with Romanian and EU flags during post-election riots in [[Moldova]]. * On May 20, 2009, American actor [[Alec Baldwin]] was declared ''persona non grata'' by the [[Philippines|Philippine government]] after an appearance in an episode of the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', where he joked about availing a "Filipino or Russian mail-order bride". Philippine senator and actor [[Ramon Revilla Jr.]] said his (Baldwin's) wife would be "unlucky" and that "there will be trouble" if Alec Baldwin were to travel to the country.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|access-date=May 20, 2009|