{{Cite check|date=October 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = <!-- (defaults to {{PAGENAME}}) --> | native_name = | native_name_lang = | flag = | flag_caption = | image = | image_caption =
| total = <!-- total population worldwide --> | total_year = <!-- year of total population --> | total_source = <!-- source of total population; may be ''census'' or ''estimate'' --> | total_ref = <!-- references supporting total population --> | genealogy = | regions = [[United States]] | languages = [[American English]] | philosophies = | religions = [[Christianity]] (primarily [[Protestantism]]) | related_groups = [[Old Stock Canadians]], [[British people|British]], [[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scots]], [[Welsh people|Welsh]], [[Ulster-Scots]] | footnotes = }} '''Old Stock Americans''', '''Old Pioneer Stock''', or '''Anglo-Americans''' are people who are descended from the original settlers of the [[Thirteen Colonies]],<ref name="boundless">{{cite web|title=Boundless U.S. History: Immigration|url=https://www.boundless.com/u-s-history/textbooks/boundless-u-s-history-textbook/religion-romanticism-and-cultural-reform-1820-1860-14/immigration-118/nativism-626-8562/|website=Boundless.com|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> of mostly [[British people|British]] ancestry, who immigrated in the 17th and the 18th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brookhiser|first1=Richard|title=Way of the Wasp: How It Made America, and How It Can Save It, So to Speak|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_way_of_the_WASP.html?id=8krJyUfxuz0C|publisher=Free Pr|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=English Immigration to America|url=http://www.emmigration.info/english-immigration-to-america.htm|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McClymer|first1=John F.|title=The KKK in the 1920s|url=http://www1.assumption.edu/ahc/1920s/Eugenics/Klan.html|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Limerick|first1=Patricia Nelson|title=The Legacy of Conquest: The Unbroken Past of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kk1PMykiIE4C&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=who+are+old+stock+americans&source=bl&ots=MzBAGg3-oq&sig=G5etYd-UB818xCiMHr8k1IaRcow&hl=en#v=onepage&q=who%20are%20old%20stock%20americans&f=false|publisher=W.W. Norton Company|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hirschman|first1=C.|title=Immigration and the American century|pmid=16463913|volume=42|journal=Demography|pages=595–620|doi=10.1353/dem.2005.0031}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Razib|title=Don't count old stock Anglo-America out|url=http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/gnxp/2011/08/dont-count-old-stock-anglo-america-out/#.V4bWStQrJkg|publisher=Discover Magazine|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>
==Settlement in the colonies== Between 1700 and 1775, the overwhelming majority of immigrants to the colonies (around 75%) were British immigrants of varying ethnic backgrounds such as [[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[Ulster Scots people|Scots-Irish]] and [[Welsh people|Welsh]]. Populations of [[Germans]], Dutch and others arrived with other colonial efforts but the majority were British.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rrf_HrCTXdgC&pg=PA21&dq=ethnic+groups+united+states+1775&hl=en&ei=Z1bBTO6kGIHOswbuxvzrCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=ethnic+groups+united+states+1775&f=false|title=Ethnicity in Contemporary America: A Geographical Appraisal|first=Jesse O.|last=McKee|date=21 August 2017|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|accessdate=21 August 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>
==19th Century to present== Until the late 20th century, Old Stock Americans dominated [[Americans|American]] culture and politics.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oyangen|first1=K.|title=Immigrant Identities in the Rural Midwest, 1830--1925|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KFkq3ewX81sC&pg=PA197&lpg=PA197&dq=%22old+stock+americans%22&source=bl&ots=8tA1jKQFYz&sig=LZSP5m9SPpSTEy0ECWvAoaE6i-I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLjqirz_HNAhUF4iYKHck0DuA4ChDoAQggMAE#v=onepage&q=%22old%20stock%20americans%22&f=false|publisher=Iowa State University|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lichtman|first1=Alan J.|title=Prejudice and the Old Politics: The Presidential Election of 1928|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KbGiJpDk6pwC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=old+stock+dominated+american+politics&source=bl&ots=Z38gGvU23c#v=onepage&q=old%20stock%20dominated%20american%20politics&f=false|publisher=Lexington Books|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> Thousands of [[German-Americans|Germans]] and [[Irish-Americans|Irish]] immigrated to the United States during the 19th century and were met with strong opposition from the majority [[Protestant]] Old Stock, who were anti-immigration and anti-Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Byrne|first1=Julie|title=Roman Catholics and Immigration in Nineteenth-Century America |url=http://nationalhumanitiescenter.org/tserve/nineteen/nkeyinfo/nromcath.htm|publisher=National Humanities Center|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Bill |title=AN ANTI-CATHOLIC LAW’S TROUBLING LEGACY|url=https://www.catholicleague.org/an-anti-catholic-laws-troubling-legacy-2/ |publisher=Catholic League |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>
Regardless of ancestral origin, English-speaking, native-born [[White Americans]], were referred to as Anglos or Native Americans (not to be confused with [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous Americans]]). American settlers arriving in droves to the newly acquired, formerly Spanish, French, and Mexican colonies, whether they were native born or immigrants from the British Isles, were labelled as "Anglos", especially if they did not assimilate into the cultures that inhabited the area for centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowlouisiana.org/entry/anglo-americans|title=Anglo-Americans - Know Louisiana|publisher=}}</ref>
